## Rate Limit Headers

All rate-limited responses MUST include these headers (when applicable):

| Header | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| X-RateLimit-Limit | Max requests per window | 100 |
| X-RateLimit-Remaining | Requests left in current window | 42 |
| X-RateLimit-Reset | Unix timestamp when window resets | 1709424000 |
| Retry-After | Seconds to wait (on 429 only) | 60 |

### Example Response (Success)

```http
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
X-RateLimit-Remaining: 95
X-RateLimit-Reset: 1709424060
```

### Example Response (Rate Limited)

```http
HTTP/1.1 429 Too Many Requests
X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
X-RateLimit-Remaining: 0
X-RateLimit-Reset: 1709424060
Retry-After: 60
Content-Type: application/problem+json

{
  "type": "https://api.example.com/errors/rate-limited",
  "title": "Rate Limit Exceeded",
  "status": 429,
  "detail": "You have exceeded 100 requests per minute.",
  "retry_after": 60
}
```

---

## Retry-After

- **Format**: Integer seconds (preferred) or HTTP-date
- **When**: Always on 429 responses
- **Guidance**: Client should wait at least this long before retrying

```http
Retry-After: 60
```

or

```http
Retry-After: Wed, 21 Oct 2026 07:28:00 GMT
```

---

## Client SDK Patterns

### Exponential Backoff

When receiving 429, back off before retrying:

```python
def request_with_retry(url, max_retries=3):
    for attempt in range(max_retries):
        response = requests.get(url)
        if response.status_code != 429:
            return response
        retry_after = int(response.headers.get("Retry-After", 2 ** attempt))
        time.sleep(retry_after)
    raise RateLimitExceeded("Max retries exceeded")
```

### Honor Retry-After

- Prefer `Retry-After` over custom backoff when provided
- Fall back to exponential backoff if header missing
- Do not retry immediately on 429

### Rate Limit Awareness

- Track `X-RateLimit-Remaining` to throttle before hitting limit
- Avoid bursts when remaining is low
- Log when approaching limit (e.g., remaining < 10)

---

## Tiered Limits

Document different limits per tier:

| Tier | Requests/minute | Requests/day | Burst |
|------|------------------|--------------|-------|
| Free | 60 | 1,000 | 10 |
| Pro | 300 | 50,000 | 50 |
| Enterprise | 1,000 | 500,000 | 200 |

- Apply limits per API key or per user
- Return 429 with clear message when limit exceeded
- Consider `X-RateLimit-Limit` to vary by tier

---

## Implementation Checklist

When implementing rate limiting:

- [ ] Choose algorithm (token bucket or sliding window recommended)
- [ ] Define limits per endpoint or per resource
- [ ] Include X-RateLimit-* headers in all responses
- [ ] Include Retry-After on 429 responses
- [ ] Document limits in API docs
- [ ] Log rate limit events for monitoring
- [ ] Consider per-user vs per-IP limits (authenticated vs anonymous)

---

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Why It's Bad | Correct Approach |
|--------------|--------------|-------------------|
| No Retry-After on 429 | Client cannot know when to retry | Always include Retry-After |
| Inconsistent header names | Client cannot parse | Use standard X-RateLimit-* |
| Silent rejection | Client does not know why request failed | Return 429 with clear body |
| No headers on success | Client cannot throttle proactively | Include headers on 2xx |
| Global limit only | One consumer can starve others | Per-key or per-user limits |
